
1. Artifacts and Their Functions
This part explains the different components (artifacts) that are used in the Asset Store and their purposes:

ApplicationSet: This represents one or more CMDB Applications that are managed in the store. It needs to be unique for each CMDB application.
ApplicationSetResourceType: Each ApplicationSet can have multiple resource types (for example, regions or environments). This allows you to associate different datasets with the ApplicationSet.
ResourceTypeAttributes: These are optional attributes that can be associated with resource types.
ResourceTypeActions: These are the actions that can be performed on a resource type (for example, Read, Write, Execute). These actions are managed separately.
Resource Data in PlainID:
Resources: These are the actual assets used within PlainID (essentially what you are managing in the Asset Store).
ResourceAttributes: Each resource can have one or more attributes (e.g., properties like "size" or "location"). Each attribute has a value (for example, "size": "large").
2. Main Use Cases
The API has two main use cases:

Managing Meta Data: Create and manage metadata for an application, such as application sets, resource types, and actions.
Managing Resource Data: Manage resource data, including adding, updating, and deleting resources and their attributes.
Your focus is on Use Case 1, which deals with managing the metadata (e.g., creating an application set and assigning resource types).

3. Design Approach
When working with the ApplicationSet data, the API allows you to fetch the entire object (this includes everything associated with the ApplicationSet like resource types and attributes).
When updating, you only need to provide the keys of the objects you want to modify, and the API will handle the update.
If you omit any data when updating (such as resource types), the API will remove the missing data. This means you need to provide all relevant data when making an update.

4. Creating an ApplicationSet
To create a new ApplicationSet, you need to provide a payload like this:

{
    "applicationSet": "My Application Set",
    "applicationName": "Test Set for GTS Core",
    "cmdbApplicationId": "c2345194dbb997042432e7550b9619f9"
}

the cmdbApplicationId is the unique ID of the CMDB application you're associating with the new ApplicationSet. This request will create a basic ApplicationSet.

---

5. Adding More Information to ApplicationSet
To further populate the ApplicationSet, you can add:

ApplicationSetCmdbApplicationInstances: These are instances of the CMDB Application (e.g., different environments like "Dev", "Prod").
ApplicationSetResourceTypes: These define the types of resources associated with the ApplicationSet (e.g., "Database", "Web Server"). You can also specify attributes and actions for each resource type.

{
    "applicationSet": "My Application Set",
    "applicationName": "Test Set for GTS Core",
    "cmdbApplicationId": "c2345194dbb997042432e7550b9619f9",
    "applicationSetCmdbApplicationInstances": [
        {
            "cmdbApplicationInstanceId": "4c14231d1ba8f0956c95354604bcbee"
        }
    ],
    "applicationSetResourceTypes": [
        {
            "resourceType": "Resource Type 1",
            "attributes": [
                {
                    "attribute": "Attribute Type 1",
                    "dataType": "String"
                },
                {
                    "attribute": "Attribute Type 2",
                    "dataType": "Numeric"
                }
            ],
            "actions": [
                {
                    "action": "ReadOnly"
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}


In this example:

cmdbApplicationInstanceId: This identifies a specific instance of the CMDB Application (e.g., Dev or Prod).
ResourceType: Defines what type of resource is being managed.
Attributes: These are custom properties you want to associate with the resource type (e.g., String, Numeric).
Actions: These define what actions can be performed on the resource (e.g., "ReadOnly").


---

6. Managing Resources
To fetch resources for a particular resource type, you need to specify the ApplicationSet ID, the CMDB Application ID, and the Resource Type ID.

GET /asset/api/v1/resources?cmdbApplicationId=a868ede687851d90c1cb33b80cbb3506&applicationSet=M365 - Skype for Business - tom&resourceType=ResType_tom

This will return the resources for the specified CMDB application and resource type.


----

Adding Resources and Attributes
You can add resources and their attributes by making a POST request. For example, this request adds a new resource:

{
    "resourceValue": "test resource NEW",
    "resourceAttributes": [
        {
            "attribute": "AttributeType_tom",
            "attributeValues": ["attributeValue NEW 1"]
        }
    ]
}

In this payload:

resourceValue: The name or value of the resource.
resourceAttributes: The attributes associated with the resource and their values.
This request would add or update the resource within the Asset Store.

---
Summary:
The API allows you to create, update, and manage ApplicationSets, their resource types, and associated metadata (like attributes and actions).
You can fetch, add, and modify the resources within the Asset Store.
When creating or updating an ApplicationSet, make sure to provide the required cmdbApplicationId, resource types, and actions.









----


Managing Resources:
To fetch resources of a particular type, you use a GET request: GET /asset/api/v1/resources?cmdbApplicationId=<ID>&applicationSet=<Name>&resourceType=<Type>
Example response:

{
   "resourceValue": "test resource 11",
   "resourceAttributes": [
      {
         "attribute": "AttributeType_tom",
         "attributeValues": ["second attributeValueFor-test resource 11"]
      }
   ]
}


--

Adding Resources and Attributes:
Use a POST request to add new resources and their attributes: POST /asset/api/v1/resources?cmdbApplicationId=<ID>&applicationSet=<Name>&resourceType=<Type>
Example payload:

{
   "resourceValue": "test resource NEW",
   "resourceAttributes": [
      {
         "attribute": "AttributeType_tom",
         "attributeValues": ["NEW attributeValueFor-test resource NEW"]
      }
   ]
}

---

Deleting Resources or Attributes:
You can also delete specific resources or attributes using DELETE requests. DELETE /asset/api/v1/resources Example for deleting a resource:

{
   "resourceValue": "test resource 11"
}


---

Feeding Data to PlainID:
The API provides a single call for passing data to PlainID for use as an asset source: GET /denormalisedassetdata
Example response for feeding the denormalized data:

{
   "assets": [
      {
         "applicationSet": "M365 - Skype for Business",
         "applicationName": "M365 - Skype for Business",
         "cmdbApplicationId": "a868ede687851d90c1cb33b80cbb3506",
         "cmdbApplicationInstanceIds": ["4168ede687851d90c1cb33b80cbb354b"],
         "resourceType": "ResType_0",
         "resource": "ResourceValue_1532",
         "attributeType": null,
         "attributeValues": [
            {
               "attributeType_0": "AttributeValue_5992"
            }
         ]
      }
   ]
}


Asset Store API for managing CMDB applications, Application Sets, resource types, and their attributes. It covers creating, fetching, updating,
and deleting data through the API, and also provides guidance on feeding the data into PlainID for use as an asset source.

